{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"94c48404-25bf-4c68-88fa-a428408179e3","content":"Let me also check the broader project structure for context.","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_98OZO9aNZTpuBn6ClN70y8","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-72a49a9657fd434286b925b16fa4e081"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-72a49a9657fd434286b925b16fa4e081."}],"interactionId":"ce62700c-1f53-4866-bb4d-0c722ab84c7e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. Let me check what's required for a proper dotnet template.\n\nKey issues I see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required but highly recommended for validation and editor support.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for template packs; allows multiple versions of the same template to coexist.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Works with groupIdentity for versioning.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n5. **`defaultValue` references `net9.0`** — This is fine (both .NET 8 and .NET 9 are current as of 2026, though .NET 10 may be out).\n\n\n6. **`Framework` symbol lacks `replaces` configuration** — The symbol is defined but without a `replaces` property pointing to the actual string in template files (like the `<TargetFramework>` in the .csproj), selecting a framework won't actually modify the generated project. I need to verify that the symbol is properly wired to replace the target framework value in the project file.\n7. **`sourceName` replacement is set** — \"MyWebApi\" is configured, which should work for substitutions.\n\nI should also check what other template files exist in the workspace to understand the full scope of what needs replacing.","outputTokens":461},"id":"bbad5a30-294b-42f1-900f-cf63c34f0b13","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:43:08.417Z","parentId":"29175777-dc39-4db1-ac00-093205165e37"}
